Global Voices has covered Yemen's humanitarian crisis over the years:

  * [Yemen: Millions Go Hungry in Ongoing Food Crisis](https://globalvoicesonline.org/2012/05/21/yemen-millions-go-hungry-in-ongoing-food-crisis/)
  * [Yemen: Pressing Humanitarian Needs and Deteriorating Economic Situation](https://globalvoicesonline.org/2011/08/09/yemen-pressing-humanitarian-needs-and-deteriorating-economic-situation/)

Yet the humanitarian aspect of the war doesn't seem to matter to nor make
headlines in mainstream media. IRIN warned that the humanitarian situation
will only become severe due to the conflict.

> The humanitarian situation in
> [#Yemen](https://twitter.com/hashtag/Yemen?src=hash) is dire, a civil war
> will only deepen an already acute crisis —
> [@adammbaron](https://twitter.com/adammbaron) <http://t.co/6y1Qz5ZM5s>
>
> — IRIN News (@irinnews) [March 25,
> 2015](https://twitter.com/irinnews/status/580602953448341506)

In summary, the humanitarian crisis that international organisations have been
warning about over the past years has just been exacerbated over the past week
of war in Yemen and will continue to do so. The question now is, what will the
world do about it and when?

